          <aside class="excerpt-page sample-excerpt" aria-label="An excerpt from Module 2">
            <span class="excerpt-spine" aria-hidden="true"></span>

            <header class="excerpt-page-header">
              <p class="excerpt-eyebrow">From Module 2 &mdash; Advice: Why (&amp; How) We Avoid It</p>
            </header>

            <div class="excerpt-body">
              <p class="excerpt-text">
                We engage in deeply focused, empathic, mindful listening, with an
                attitude of unconditional positive regard for the person we are
                working with. Giving advice is not counseling, and often damages
                our relationship with those we are trying to help. How can we
                break the advice habit?
              </p>
              <p class="excerpt-text">
                Counselors practice listening to others share about deep and
                often painful issues, without judging, and without immediately
                relating (&ldquo;me too&rdquo;). We avoid advice or jumping in to
                &lsquo;fix&rsquo;. We work to maintain a &lsquo;know
                nothing&rsquo;, without an agenda about what the person we are
                helping &ldquo;should&rdquo; do.
              </p>
            </div>

            <footer class="excerpt-page-footer">
              <span class="excerpt-rule" aria-hidden="true"></span>
              <p class="excerpt-attribution">
                <em>From the Module 2 flipbook.</em>
                Taught by Elizabeth Morrison.
